    {
      "id": "GSkkoRQhDvZINdhoDbGWi",
      "type": "text",
      "x": -761.3155151968643,
      "y": -1508.6018386724063,
      "width": 1059.7227974807718,
      "height": 225,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "b0t",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 2131730749,
      "version": 938,
      "versionNonce": 1822931517,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": null,
      "updated": 1780300977551,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "In metacat we represent computation as separate monoidal structures (data and control). \nCompileGraph is a graph representation of metacat collecting a \"bundle\" of hypergraphs.\nIn order to generate a program we need to \"merge\" the two theories since control and data usually coexist\nin program.\nFor doing that, we generate a flowchart (CFG in code) that is a graph of nodes that contains blocks of\ninstructions and are wired together (see example of node on the right).\nA flowchart is not a strucured program (it can have arbitrary gotos), we need to apply Ramsey to extract\nthe final structured program.\n",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "In metacat we represent computation as separate monoidal structures (data and control). \nCompileGraph is a graph representation of metacat collecting a \"bundle\" of hypergraphs.\nIn order to generate a program we need to \"merge\" the two theories since control and data usually coexist in program.\nFor doing that, we generate a flowchart (CFG in code) that is a graph of nodes that contains blocks of instructions and are wired together (see example of node on the right).\nA flowchart is not a strucured program (it can have arbitrary gotos), we need to apply Ramsey to extract the final structured program.\n",
      "autoResize": false,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
